  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Money laundering prohibitions have a complex legal history that developed over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime in the 1920s and 1930s\n- Initially focused on preventing criminals from hiding proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Key Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, United States)\n- First comprehensive legislation targeting financial concealment\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created international standards for anti-money laundering regulations\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for global implementation\n\n4. Significant Legislative Expansions:\n- United States Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a distinct federal offense\n- Established comprehensive reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded money laundering prohibitions\n- Increased financial institution reporting requirements\n- Strengthened counter-terrorism financial tracking\n\n6. Global Harmonization:\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Standardized legal frameworks across multiple jurisdictions\n- Enhanced cross-border investigation capabilities\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving with technological and financial innovations.",
